function #

partial #

partial<T>() #

import { partial } from "trine/function/partial";

Returns a version of the function that has given parameters prefilled and passes given parameters through to the original, denoted by placeholders.

Parameters #
  • this T
  • ...staticParams any
Returns #
  • T
examples #
Unary parseInt #
parseInt::partial(_)("10", 2) // 10
Hexadecimal parseInt #
parseInt::partial(_, 16)("10") // 16
Fill Only the Second Argument #
function foo (a, b, c, d) {
  console.log(a, b, c, d);
}

foo::partial(_, 2, ___)(1, 3, 4) // logs "1 2 3 4"
Fill Only the Second Last Argument #
function foo (a, b, c, d) {
  console.log(a, b, c, d);
}

foo::partial(___, 3, _)(1, 2, 4) // logs "1 2 3 4"
Compose a Prototype Method #
const slice1 = Array.prototype.slice::partial(1, ___);
[1, 2, 3, 4]::slice1() // [2, 3, 4]

convolve #

convolve<rT, iT>() #

import { convolve } from "trine/iterable/convolve";

Maps the iterator with the additional tail of k previous items. k is determined by the number of items in the accumulation iterator.

Type Parameters #
  • rT The item type of the returned iterator.
  • iT The item type of the input iterator.
Parameters #
  • this Iterable<iT>
  • accumulator (_this : iT, tail : iT) => rT
  • tail Iterable<iT>
Returns #
  • Iterable<rT>
examples #
Basic Usage #
[1,2,3].convolve(function (tail) {
  return [...tail, this].reduce(add);
}, [0, -1]) // yields 0, 3, 6

quickSort #

quickSort<T>() #

import { quickSort } from "trine/iterable/quickSort";

A pure JS alternative to the builtin sort - operates directly on iterators, so it can be advantageous to native sort in cases where you only need a few of the sorted items, e.g. 15 first products sorted by price. The first items get sorted precisely first so the whole set does not necessarily need to be sorted.

Parameters #
  • this Iterable<T>
  • comparator (_this: T, b : T) => number
Returns #
  • Iterable<T>
examples #
Basic Usage #
[3,2,5,1,4]::quickSort(function (b) {
  return this - b;
}); // yields 1,2,3,4,5

tee #

tee<T>() #

import { tee } from "trine/iterable/tee";

Yields forks of the original iterator, caching the items as needed.

Parameters #
  • this Iterable<T>
Returns #
  • Iterable<Iterable<T>>
examples #
Basic Usage #
const source = [1,2,3]::map(function () { return this * 2});
const forks = source::tee();
const a = forks.next().value;
const b = forks.next().value;
[...a] // [1,2,3]
[...b] // [1,2,3]

to #

to<iT, rT>() #

import { to } from "trine/iterable/to";

Unwraps the iterator into a collection.

Parameters #
  • this Iterable<iT>
  • Type Function The constructor for the collection type.
Returns #
  • rT
examples #
Arrays #
[1,2,3].map(function () {
  return this * 2;
})::to(Array) // returns [2, 4, 6]
Objects #
[{id: "a"}, {id: "b"}].map(function () {
  return [this.id, this];
})::to(Object); // returns { a: { id: "a" }, b: { id: "b"} }
Strings #
"foo".split("").reverse()::to(String) // "oof"


@example Other Collections

```javascript
[2.5, 3.5]::to(Uint16Array) // returns Uint16Array [2, 3]
["foo", "bar", "foo"]::to(Set) // returns Set ["foo", "bar"]
[["x", "y"], ["z", "n"]]::to(Map) // returns Map { "x": "y", "z": "n" }

uniq #

uniq<T>() #

import { uniq } from "trine/iterable/uniq";

Yields the items that aren't equal to the previous item based on a comparator.

Parameters #
  • this Iterable<T>
  • comparator (_this : T, b : T) => boolean The function to assert equality of the items.
Returns #
  • Iterable<T>
examples #
Basic Usage #
[{
  id: 1,
}, {
  id: 1,
}, {
  id: 2,
}]::uniq(function (b) {
  return this.id === b.id;
}); // yields { id: 1 } and { id: 2 }

[{
  id: 1,
}, {
  id: 2,
}, {
  id: 1,
}]::uniq(function (b) {
  return this.id === b.id;
}); // yields { id: 1 }, { id: 2 } and { id: 1 }
Unique Characters in a String #
"bcabbbac"::sortAlphabetically()::uniq(equals) // yields "a", "b", "c"

5::sub(-5) // returns 10
